Day 20 Activity: Hierarchical Clustering of Colleges - SOLUTIONS

Your Name

ECON 122

Introduction

In this activity, youll use hierarchical clustering to group colleges based on their characteristics. Unlike K-means clustering which requires you to specify the number of clusters beforehand, hierarchical clustering produces a dendrogram (tree) that shows the relationships between all cases, allowing you to choose the number of clusters after exploring the data structure.

Learning Goals:

  • Apply hierarchical clustering to real data
  • Interpret and visualize dendrograms
  • Understand different linkage methods
  • Cut dendrograms to create cluster assignments
  • Compare hierarchical clustering to K-means

Time: Approximately 40 minutes

Setup

Load the necessary packages:

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(readr)
library(tidyr)

Note: This activity uses the dendextend package for coloring dendrograms. If you dont have it installed, you can install it with:

install.packages("dendextend")

Part 1: Load and Explore the Data (5 minutes)

Well use college data from California and Massachusetts. Limiting to these two states will make the dendrogram readable while still providing interesting diversity in school types.

# Load the college data from CSV
colleges <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mgelman/data/master/Colleges.csv")

# Create derived variables and select variables of interest
college_data <- colleges %>%
  mutate(
    avg_sat = (SATM + SATV) / 2,           # Average SAT score
    adm_rate = AppsAccept / AppsReceive,   # Admission rate
    cost = Tuition + RoomBoard + Books      # Total cost
  ) %>%
  # Select our variables of interest
  select(College, State, 
         avg_sat,        # Average SAT score
         adm_rate,       # Admission rate  
         HStop10,        # % of students from top 10% of HS class
         cost,           # Total cost
         Ratio,          # Student/faculty ratio
         Donate,         # % of alumni who donate
         AvgSalary,      # Average alumni salary
         FullTime        # Number of full-time students
  ) %>%
  # Filter for only CA and MA colleges
  filter(State %in% c("CA", "MA")) %>%
  # Remove rows with missing data
  filter(complete.cases(.))

# How many colleges remain after filtering?
nrow(college_data)
## [1] 40

Part 2: Creating Your First Dendrogram (10 minutes)

For hierarchical clustering, we need the numeric variables only (not school names or state):

# Create a dataset with only the clustering variables
cluster_vars <- college_data %>%
  select(avg_sat, adm_rate, HStop10, cost, Ratio, Donate, AvgSalary, FullTime)

Before we cluster, remember that hierarchical clustering uses distance measures, so we should standardize:

# Standardize the clustering variables
cluster_vars_scaled <- scale(cluster_vars)

Well use the dendextend package to help us color the Claremont Colleges in our dendrograms:

# Load dendextend package for dendrogram customization
library(dendextend)

Why color the Claremont Colleges? By highlighting the Claremont Colleges in red throughout our dendrograms, we can easily track where they appear in the tree structure and verify that they cluster with similar elite institutions. This visual aid helps us interpret the results more effectively.

Important Note on dendrogram labels: To display college names (instead of numbers) in our dendrograms, we must set the row names of our data matrix to the college names BEFORE running the clustering. This is done in Q2. Once set, all dendrograms will automatically show college names as labels, with the Claremont Colleges appearing in red.

Better label spacing: To make college names easier to read, we use:

  1. Large figure sizes (fig.height=8, fig.width=10 in the chunk options)
  2. Increased bottom margins (mar = c(15, 4, 4, 2)) to give labels plenty of room
  3. Appropriate label size (cex = 0.6-0.7) for readability

This combination ensures college names are clearly visible without overlapping!

Q2: Use the dist() function to compute the distance matrix between all colleges using the scaled data. Then use hclust() to perform hierarchical clustering with complete linkage (the default). Store the result as hc_complete.

# IMPORTANT: Set row names to college names so dendrogram shows names not numbers
rownames(cluster_vars_scaled) <- college_data$College

# Step 1: Compute distance matrix
d <- dist(cluster_vars_scaled)

# Step 2: Run hierarchical clustering
hc_complete <- hclust(d)

Q3: Plot the dendrogram using plot(). Based on the dendrogram, approximately how many natural clusters do you see? (Dont worry about being exact - just give your initial impression)

# Load dendextend for easy label coloring
library(dendextend)

# Create color vector to highlight Claremont Colleges in red

# Create dendrogram object and color the labels
# Because we set rownames in Q2, the dendrogram labels are college names (not numbers!)
dend <- as.dendrogram(hc_complete)
labels_colors(dend) <- label_colors[order.dendrogram(dend)]

# Plot the colored dendrogram with all college names as labels

Part 5: Comparing Linkage Methods (10 minutes)

Hierarchical clustering can use different linkage methods to compute distances between clusters. Lets compare complete linkage (what weve been using) with average linkage.

Q10: Perform hierarchical clustering again using average linkage instead of complete linkage. Create the dendrogram and compare it visually to the complete linkage dendrogram.

# Perform hierarchical clustering with average linkage
# Uses the same distance matrix d (which has college names as labels)
hc_average <- hclust(d, method = "average")

# Create dendrogram objects with colored labels for Claremont Colleges
dend_complete <- as.dendrogram(hc_complete)
dend_average <- as.dendrogram(hc_average)

# Color the labels (red for Claremont Colleges)
labels_colors(dend_complete) <- label_colors[order.dendrogram(dend_complete)]
labels_colors(dend_average) <- label_colors[order.dendrogram(dend_average)]

# Plot both dendrograms side by side 
par(mfrow = c(1, 2), mar = c(13, 4, 4, 2))  # 2 plots, large bottom margin
plot(dend_complete, main = "Complete Linkage\n(Claremont in Red)", 
     xlab = "", sub = "", cex = 0.6)
plot(dend_average, main = "Average Linkage\n(Claremont in Red)", 
     xlab = "", sub = "", cex = 0.6)

par(mfrow = c(1, 1), mar = c(5, 4, 4, 2))  # Reset to defaults

Your answer:

The two dendrograms show some differences:

  1. Height scale: The average linkage dendrogram has a smaller overall height compared to complete linkage, with fusions happening at lower heights
  2. Tree structure: The branching patterns are somewhat different. Complete linkage tends to create more distinct, separated clusters, while average linkage produces a more chained structure
  3. Cluster balance: Complete linkage tends to produce more balanced clusters, while average linkage may create some more elongated chains
  4. Overall pattern: Despite these differences, the major groupings are relatively similar - elite schools still cluster together, less selective schools cluster together, etc.

Part 6: Reflection Questions

Q12: What are the main advantages of hierarchical clustering compared to K-means clustering? What are the disadvantages?

Your answer:

Advantages:

  1. No need to specify K beforehand: You can explore the dendrogram and choose the number of clusters after seeing the data structure
  2. Provides rich visualization: The dendrogram shows not just cluster membership but also the relationships and similarities between all observations
  3. Deterministic: Given the same linkage method and distance measure, you always get the same result (no random initialization like K-means)
  4. Hierarchical structure: You can see clusters at multiple levels of granularity simultaneously
  5. Works with any distance measure: Not limited to Euclidean distance

Disadvantages:

  1. Computationally expensive: O(n) for distance matrix computation and O(n log n) for clustering, making it impractical for very large datasets (K-means is much faster)
  2. Cannot revise: Once two clusters are merged, they cannot be unmerged (K-means can reassign points in each iteration)
  3. Sensitive to outliers: Particularly with complete and single linkage methods
  4. Choice of linkage: Results can vary substantially depending on the linkage method chosen
  5. No objective function: Unlike K-means which minimizes within-cluster variation, hierarchical clustering doesnt optimize a clear objective

Q13: Why is it still important to standardize variables before performing hierarchical clustering, even though it creates a tree structure?

Your answer:

Standardization is crucial for hierarchical clustering because:

  1. Distance calculations: Hierarchical clustering relies on distance measures (typically Euclidean distance) to determine similarity. If variables are on different scales, variables with larger ranges will dominate the distance calculations
  2. Example: In our college data, FullTime (number of students) ranges from hundreds to thousands, while adm_rate (admission rate) ranges from 0 to 1. Without standardization, differences in enrollment would completely overwhelm differences in admission rates
  3. Equal weighting: Standardization ensures that each variable contributes equally to the clustering decision, which is usually what we want when we include multiple variables
  4. Interpretability: With standardized variables, the height of the dendrogram represents distance in terms of standard deviations, making it easier to interpret

Just like with K-means, failing to standardize can lead to clusters that are driven almost entirely by the variables with the largest scales, missing important patterns in other variables.

Q14: In hierarchical clustering, you can cut the tree at different heights to get different numbers of clusters. How is this different from running K-means multiple times with different K values? Which approach do you find more intuitive?

Your answer:

Differences:

  1. Single analysis vs.multiple runs:
    • Hierarchical: Build the tree once, then cut it at different heights - all potential K values come from one analysis
    • K-means: Must run the algorithm separately for each K value you want to try
  2. Relationships between solutions:
    • Hierarchical: Cutting at different heights creates nested clusters (smaller clusters are contained within larger clusters)
    • K-means: Each K gives an independent solution - clusters from K=3 are not necessarily related to clusters from K=4
  3. Visualization:
    • Hierarchical: The dendrogram shows all possible cluster solutions simultaneously
    • K-means: Need separate plots (like elbow plots) to compare different K values
  4. Decision process:
    • Hierarchical: Choose where to cut based on visual inspection of gaps in the dendrogram
    • K-means: Choose K based on elbow plot or other criteria like within-cluster sum of squares

Which is more intuitive?

I find hierarchical clustering more intuitive because:

  • The dendrogram provides a complete picture of the data structure at all levels
  • You can see the story of how clusters merge together
  • Its easier to identify natural groupings by looking for large jumps in height
  • However, K-means is more intuitive in terms of the optimization goal (minimize within-cluster variation)

Both have their place depending on the analysis goals and data size.

Q15: Looking at your final clusters, do you think the hierarchical clustering method captured meaningful groupings of colleges? If you were a prospective student using this analysis, how might it help you identify schools to consider?

Your answer:

Yes, the hierarchical clustering captured very meaningful groupings of colleges within our California and Massachusetts dataset. The clusters clearly separate schools by:

  1. Selectivity level: Elite/highly selective (top-tier universities and liberal arts colleges) vs.moderately selective vs.less selective
  2. Cost: Expensive private schools vs.more affordable options
  3. Student body characteristics: High-achieving student bodies (high SAT scores, top 10% HS students) vs.more diverse academic profiles
  4. Institutional type: Small liberal arts colleges vs.larger research universities vs.regional universities

As a prospective student, this analysis would be helpful because:

  1. Find similar schools: If Im interested in one school (e.g., Pomona College), I can look at others in the same cluster to find schools with similar characteristics
  2. Geographic comparison: Since we have both CA and MA schools, I can see which schools on the East Coast are similar to my California preferences (or vice versa). For example, if I like the Claremont Colleges in California, I can find similar small liberal arts colleges in Massachusetts
  3. Target appropriate schools: The clusters help identify schools where my academic profile (SAT scores, etc.) would be competitive
  4. Explore alternatives: I might discover schools I hadnt considered that are similar to my top choices
  5. Financial planning: Clusters help group schools by cost, helping with financial planning
  6. Balanced list: I could select schools from different clusters to create a balanced application list (reach, target, and safety schools)

For example, if Im interested in Pomona College in California but want to explore East Coast alternatives, looking at the other schools in its cluster would show me which Massachusetts liberal arts colleges have similar profiles. Similarly, a Massachusetts student interested in highly selective schools can discover that the Claremont Colleges are West Coast alternatives with similar characteristics.

tanglegram(dend_list, 
           highlight_distinct_edges = FALSE,
           common_subtrees_color_lines = TRUE,
           margin_inner = 5,  # Space between the two dendrograms
           lwd = 0.5,
           edge.lwd = 0.5,
           lab.cex = 0.5)

The tanglegram shows the relationship between the two hierarchical clustering methods. Lines connect the same colleges in both dendrograms, and the crossing of lines indicates differences in the clustering structure between the two methods. Despite some differences, we can see that the overall structure is relatively similar, with most schools maintaining similar positions in both trees. The Claremont Colleges (shown in red labels) can be tracked across both dendrograms to see if they remain grouped together under both linkage methods.
